{"key":"post-9977040","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9977040</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;so i was wondering if i could just put a water source inside the box itself and use a fish tank bubbler to produce the moisture in the air to use as a substitute for the misting. would this work? &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;No.&amp;nbsp; For proper pinning performance, your cakes need to dry out slightly, and then have that moisture replaced. This is the number 1 pinning trigger. If you gave them a steady stream of water to prevent drying, performance would be poor, or non-existent.&amp;nbsp; You need to mist.&amp;nbsp; The level of automation to duplicate the human eyeballs and brain/hand coordination hasn't been developed yet.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>9976942</prev>\n<first>9976644</first>\n<last>9977040</last>\n<when>1237154866</when>\n<utime>03/16/09 01:07 AM</utime>\n</post>"}